86. Quis totidem .· se. avus—Quis . . . avus: ‘ which of our ancestors ever supped in private on seven dishes.' The ancient Roman nobles, to display their munificence, were in the habit of giving costly entertainments to their friends and dependants ε but the rich men oflatter times excluded them, and sat down to sumptuous entertainments, provided for themselves alone.
